= Teaching Statement

My aspiration as an educator aligns deeply with Cornell's mission to advance learning, discovery, and public engagement. I seek to make economics not merely an academic subject but a practical toolkit that empowers every student to analyze complex social and policy issues critically. Grounded in political economy and public economics, my teaching philosophy prioritizes clarity and experiential learning, both essential in cultivating analytical rigor while nurturing inclusivity and accessibility in the classroom. I translate complex economic theories into accessible language, bridging formal analytical frameworks with intuitive understanding, thereby respecting diverse student backgrounds and embracing Cornell’s commitment to community belonging.

In practice, this means fostering an active, supportive learning environment where students engage with economic concepts through problem-solving workshops and collaborative discourse, reflecting the department's values of interdisciplinary inquiry and real-world relevance. By facilitating hands-on application and encouraging questions in a low-pressure setting, I nurture the confidence and critical thinking necessary for success in modern economic discourse and policy analysis. Positive student evaluations of my approach underscore the effectiveness of this method in fostering both mastery and enthusiasm.

I am committed to contributing to Cornell’s open, collaborative, and diverse intellectual environment by incorporating public service perspectives into teaching and research, thereby preparing students to become informed global citizens. My pedagogy is designed not only to teach economics but to inspire civic engagement, echoing Cornell’s vision of impactful scholarship that advances social welfare. Overall, my integrated approach supports the department’s emphasis on theoretical rigor, interdisciplinary collaboration, and inclusivity, enabling me to contribute meaningfully as an active participant in Cornell’s vibrant academic community.
